premise_source_doc_sentence: The zen monastery Enso-ji Il Cerchio  (  Japanese : 円相寺 , Ensō-ji ; eng. : `` Temple of the Circle ''  )  refers to a buddhist community and a cultural association recognised by the Italian Government , according to Soto Zen Buddhism , founded by the Italian Zen Master Carlo Zendo Tetsugen Serra  (  1953 -  )  , He was disciple of the Japanese Zen Master Ban Tetsugyu Soin  (  伴鐵牛 , 1910-1996  )  , between the late 1980s and the early 1990s .

For many years in Chicago he headed a betsuin  (  branch temple  )  of Chozen-ji , as well as International Zen Dojo Sogenkai , a lay Zen organization he founded to promulgate the teachings of the late Zen master , swordsman and calligrapher Omori Sogen .

While some are now the homes of wealthy communities in major cities  (  such as Zen Center of Los Angeles  )  , and some are in traditional mountain settings  (  such as Yokoji Zen Mountain Center  )  , other Zen centers have either humble or no permanent physical location - meeting in members private homes , university classrooms , and Quaker Meeting Houses to name but a few examples .
The phrase Zen center was coined by American students of Shunryu Suzuki in the mid-twentieth century , and the San Francisco Zen Center became the first Zen center , incorporating in 1962 .
While large and established Zen centers may serve as the residence of priests , monks , and lay people , smaller and more rural Zen centers may have no ordained members .
